The federal government has urged Bishop Matthew Kukah to use his high ecclesiastical office to work for religious harmony in Nigeria rather than indulge in actions that are capable of dividing the country along religious lines. This was contained in a statement by the minister of Information and Culture, Alhaji Lai Mohammed, and made available to journalists yesterday in Abuja. It said the statement credited to Bishop Kukah, in which he compared the federal government with Boko Haram, is not only disingenuous, but also a great disservice to the men and women in uniform who are daily battling the Boko Haram and ISWAP terrorists to keep all Nigerians safe. The statement said the minister reiterated the federal government’s position that the Boko Haram and ISWAP terrorists do not subscribe to any religion, irrespective of their pretence to such, but are driven by their primitive propensity to kill mindlessly and destroy without restrain, irrespective of their victims’ creed, gender or tribe. ‘’To now attribute the actions of this mad bunch to an orchestrated and systematic plan to elevate one religion over the other or decimate adherents of a particular religion is not only unfortunate but divisive, incendiary and insensitive,’’ it said. It stated he appealed to religious leaders to be more circumspect in their comments, especially on religious issues because of the deeply emotive nature of religion and the tendency for it to be exploited for political gains by naysayers.